
The Open Document Format Alliance (ODF Alliance) is a Washington, D.C.-based lobbying organization established by IBM, Sun Microsystems and SIIA to "promote and advance the use of OpenDocument Format (ODF) as the primary document format for governments" [tpl]cite web | url = http://www.odfalliance.org/mission.php | title = ODF Alliance Mission Statement | accessdate = 2008-04-23 | author =  Author Unknown[/tpl] Although originally focused on promotion of ODF "via legislation or by executive policy decision",[tpl]cite web | url = http://www.computerworld.com/action/article.do?command=printArticleBasic&articleId=9022878 | title = Microsoft trounces pro-ODF forces in state battles over open document formats | accessdate = 2008-04-23 | author =  Eric Lai and Gregg Keizer[/tpl] the ODF Alliance also did extensive PR and lobbying in opposition to the Microsoft-backed Office Open XML standard.[tpl]cite web | url = http://www.odfalliance.org/resources/TheCaseAgainstOOXML.pdf | title = The Case against OOXML | accessdate = 2008-04-23 | author =  Author Unknown[/tpl]
Founded by IBM, Sun and 33 other companies and organizations on March 3, 2006,[tpl]cite web | url = http://www.odfalliance.org/press/Release%2020060303.pdf | title = Alliance Formed to Promote Improved Access to and Retrieval of Electronic Government Documents | accessdate = 2008-04-23 | author =  Author Unknown[/tpl] the Alliance now boasts more than 500 members.[tpl]cite web | url = http://www.odfalliance.org/press/Release20080103.pdf | title = Significant Milestones, Continued Momentum for ODF Highlighted in 2007 Annual Report | accessdate = 2008-04-23 | author =  Author Unknown[/tpl]  However funding sources are not itemized in the organization's 2007 annual report, so membership financial participation is unclear.  
The ODF Alliance does not give a physical location on their website, but from documents filed with the State of New York,[tpl]cite web | url = http://www.odfalliance.org/resources/NY_RFPC.pdf | title = CIO/OFT Request for Public Comment (RFPC) # 122807 | accessdate = 2008-04-23 | author =  Mario Marchich[/tpl] the ODF Alliance appears to be headquartered at 1090 Vermont Avenue, NW, 6th Floor Washington, DC 20005, sharing offices with the Software & Information Industry Association (SIIA), one of the original backers of the ODF Alliance.

==Staff==

Marino Marcich - Executive Director. Prior to joining the ODF Alliance, Marcich was a four-year veteran of the Bush administration State Department.  While at the Department of State, he was part of former Secretary of State Colin Powell's inner circle.[tpl]cite web | url = http://www.spinwatch.org/content/view/1849/9/ | title = Spinwatch Lobbying World | accessdate = 2008-04-23 | author =  Spinwatch[/tpl] [tpl]Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot[/tpl]  Prior to joining the Bush administration, "Marcich also served as the National Association of Manufacturers (NAM) assistant vice president for international economic affairs, leading key lobby campaigns for World Trade Organization accession and trade-promotion authority."[tpl]cite web | url = http://www.spinwatch.org/content/view/1849/9/ | title = Spinwatch Lobbying World | accessdate = 2008-04-23 | author =  Spinwatch[/tpl] [tpl]Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot[/tpl]
Kathyrn Brownlee, Public Relations (Rational PR)  Public Relations for the ODF Alliance is handled by Rational PR.  Although Rational PR does not list the ODF Alliance as a client as of April 2008, SIIA is listed.[tpl]cite web | url = http://www.rationalpr.com/whoweworkfor.html | title = Rational PR: who we work for | accessdate = 2008-04-23 | author =  Author Unknown[/tpl]

==Structure==

The ODF Alliance website provides no information on funding or management structure.  At this time, the website lists 6 "national chapters" outside of the United States; Brazil, Europe, India, Malaysia, Poland and Portugal, but it is unclear if those chapter organizations have any input into the policy decisions of the organization.[tpl]cite web | url = http://www.odfalliance.org/memberlist.php | title = Memberlist | accessdate = 2008-04-23 | author =  Author Unknown[/tpl]

==Activities==

ODF Preferences

The ODF Alliance has also been very active in lobbying U.S. State and International governments on ODF issues to promote legislative mandates for the use of the ODF document format.   The ODF Alliance has provided public testimony in the following fora:
* 2008 April 9: Testimony before the Government Reform Committee, State of Texas;[tpl]cite web | url = http://consortiuminfo.org/standardsblog/article.php?story=2008040911004525| title = At the Texas Hearing on Electronic Documents | accessdate = 2008-04-23 | author =  Andy Updegrove[/tpl]
* 2007 February 7: Newsletter to ODF Alliance Members;[ref]
</ref> 
* 2007 April 17: AB 1668 California Assembly Bill: Bill Analysis.[ref]
</ref> 
Anti-OOXML

During late 2007 though 2008, the ODF Alliance was focused on lobbying ISO members in order to prevent OOXML from being accepted by ISO.  
* Ongoing: OOXML Updates and Analysis;[tpl]cite web | url = http://www.odfalliance.org/resources.php| title = OOXML Updates and Analysis | accessdate = 2008-04-23 | author =  Unknown[/tpl]
* 2007 June 7: "ODF Alliance posts documents about OOXML/OpenXML/whatever";[tpl]cite web | url = http://www.sutor.com/newsite/blog-open/?p=1694| title = ODF Alliance posts documents about OOXML/OpenXML/whatever | accessdate = 2008-04-23 | author =  Bob Sutor, IBM[/tpl]
* 2008 February 25: Open Forum Europe Geneva Conference.[tpl]cite web | url = http://www.openforumeurope.org/geneva/geneva-supporters.pdf/view| title = Open Forum Europe Supporters | accessdate = 2008-04-23 | author =  OFE[/tpl] [tpl]Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot[/tpl]

